Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: While the original idea presents a strong foundation—using RoBERTa as a diagnostic probe for political bias in generated summaries—it primarily treats the classifier as a static detector and focuses on post-hoc analysis. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1 (BiasAlert), I recognize the need for *dynamic adaptability* in open-text settings; from Paper 2 (BiasWipe), the power of *intervention via interpretability*; and from Paper 3, the importance of *quantifying uncertainty and cognitive-like biases* in model behavior. My key insight is that rather than merely evaluating whether RoBERTa can detect bias, we should investigate whether it can be transformed into an *active, self-aware auditing system* that not only identifies but also *explains, quantifies uncertainty in its own judgments*, and *guides corrective editing* in real time. This shifts the paradigm from passive detection to interactive debiasing. The novelty lies in integrating three under-explored dimensions: (1) uncertainty calibration as a proxy for detection reliability, (2) human-in-the-loop refinement guided by both model confidence and explanation, and (3) a feedback-driven architecture where the classifier informs generative models how to revise outputs to reduce bias—without retraining. Unlike prior work that either detects or mitigates bias in isolation, this framework unifies detection, interpretation, uncertainty estimation, and intervention within a single pipeline, making it more suitable for real-world deployment in high-stakes domains like journalism or policy summarization.

