  "Idea": "This research introduces 'StanceCalibrator', a novel interactive framework that transforms a fine-tuned RoBERTa-based political stance classifier into an adaptive, uncertainty-aware, and intervention-capable auditor of AI-generated summaries. Rather than treating bias detection as a binary or categorical task, StanceCalibrator operationalizes detection as a continuous process involving three stages: (1) sensitive identification of emergent political leaning through minimal linguistic perturbations, (2) calibrated confidence scoring with uncertainty quantification to flag low-reliability predictions, and (3) actionable feedback generation that guides human or automated editors in reducing detected bias while preserving factual integrity. The core innovation is the integration of Bayesian deep learning techniques (e.g., Monte Carlo dropout) to estimate predictive uncertainty, enabling the system to distinguish between clear-cut cases of bias and ambiguous instances (e.g., irony, negation, or ideologically neutral framing). We further enhance explainability by coupling SHAP-based feature attributions with natural language rationales generated via prompt engineering on large language models (e.g., Llama-3), creating interpretable justifications for each prediction. These rationales are then used in a novel 'edit-guidance' protocol: users receive both the predicted stance and a suggested revision path (e.g., 'Replace 'reckless spending' with 'increased budget allocation' to reduce left-leaning negative valence'). A crowdsourced study evaluates whether such guidance improves human ability to neutralize bias compared to unassisted editing. Crucially, we introduce a 'confidence delta' metric—measuring how much model confidence changes after edits—to assess the coherence and effectiveness of the feedback loop. We validate the framework on both expert-perturbed summaries and LLM-generated summaries across polarizing topics (e.g., climate policy, immigration). By analyzing failure modes not just in terms of accuracy but also in miscalibration (overconfident false positives/negatives), we identify conditions under which the classifier should be trusted or deferred to human judgment. This work advances the field by proposing that trustworthy AI auditing requires not just sensitivity and explainability, but also humility—knowing when it does not know.",
