  "Idea": "This research proposes a comprehensive framework to evaluate whether a fine-tuned RoBERTa-based political stance classifier can serve as a sensitive, reliable, and explainable detector of emergent political bias in AI-generated summaries. Rather than treating bias detection as a standard classification task, we reframe the classifier as a diagnostic probe within a controlled experimental pipeline. The core innovation lies in constructing a perturbation-based benchmark dataset where neutral or balanced summaries are systematically altered through minimal, semantically coherent edits that introduce subtle political leaning (e.g., lexical substitutions, framing shifts, or valence modulation). These edits are grounded in established linguistic theories of bias and ideology, ensuring ecological validity. We then assess the RoBERTa classifier’s ability to detect these incremental changes, measuring its sensitivity threshold—i.e., at what point does a summary cross the perceptibility boundary of bias? To evaluate robustness, we compare performance against partial-input baselines (inspired by Paper 3) to determine whether predictions rely on context-sensitive reasoning or surface-level cues. Furthermore, drawing from Paper 2, we conduct a human-subject study where participants are shown model-generated attributions (via attention weights, LIME, or SHAP) and asked to edit summaries to either amplify or suppress perceived bias. Success is measured by the extent to which human edits align with model predictions and lead to desired confidence shifts. Finally, we analyze failure modes: when does the classifier miss bias (false negatives) or over-detect it (false positives), particularly in cases involving irony, negation, or complex syntactic structures (echoing Paper 1’s findings on logical fragility)? The ultimate goal is to establish conditions under which such classifiers are trustworthy diagnostic tools—identifying not just *that* bias exists, but *how* it emerge